The analytics stack: Athena, Glue, E-M-R, and OpenSearch.

Four services complete the analytics picture around Redshift, all sitting on S3 as the data lake. Athena is serverless S-Q-L over data in S3: no infrastructure, no loading; you point Athena at S3 objects, via the Glue Data Catalog, write S-Q-L, and pay per terabyte scanned. It's for data-lake querying when a full warehouse is overkill: log analysis, ad-hoc analyst queries, and dashboards over Parquet in S3. Athena and Redshift Spectrum look similar from the outside; the distinction is that Spectrum is part of a Redshift cluster and uses cluster pricing, while Athena is fully standalone. Use Athena when you don't already have Redshift, and use Spectrum when you do.

Glue is managed E-T-L plus the Glue Data Catalog, the metastore for tables in S3. Glue crawlers scan S3 and infer table schemas into the catalog, which Athena, Spectrum, and E-M-R all read from. Glue E-T-L jobs are serverless Spark, billed per D-P-U-second, to run extract-transform-load pipelines. The catalog is the shared source of truth for what tables exist in the lake.

E-M-R is managed Hadoop and Spark: the full open-source big-data ecosystem, including Spark, Hive, Presto, HBase, and Flink, on a managed cluster, for custom or heavy processing that Glue's serverless Spark doesn't fit. And OpenSearch is managed full-text search and log analytics, the Elasticsearch fork, with OpenSearch Dashboards. It's for search, observability, and log exploration, and a very common pairing is DynamoDB Streams into OpenSearch, to add search over operational data.
